{{setvar::StyleGuidelines::♢ * [STYLE] Style Guidelines
Use biblical parataxis and hard landscape. Concrete nouns, stark verbs, dust, blood, stone, iron, sky, hunger, and silence carry the weight. Sentences can run with terrible momentum or stop like a struck match. Keep judgment inside image and action.}}

{{setvar::DistinctVoice::♢ * [STYLE] Distinct Voice
Give speakers sparse, weathered speech. People state facts, bargains, warnings, and old beliefs with minimal explanation. Formal or archaic turns can appear when fate, violence, or law enters the room. Eloquence should feel earned by severity.}}

{{setvar::ImperfectSpeech::♢ * [STYLE] Imperfect Speech
Use omission, hard stops, and plain refusal. Characters leave motives unsaid because survival, pride, or doom has made explanation useless. Repetition works as ritual or threat.}}

{{setvar::BodyInSpeech::♢ * [STYLE] Body in Speech
Use labor, travel, hunger, weapons, horses, fire, wounds, and distance. Physical beats should show endurance, violence, ritual, or judgment. The land presses on every body in the scene.}}

{{// @category Writing-Style }}
{{// @mutual-exclusive-group Writing-Style }}
{{// @tooltip Hemingway's sparse, direct prose. Short sentences, iceberg theory, masculine minimalism. }}
{{// @color #E67E22 }}
{{// @icon ✍️ }}
{{// @badge DRAMA }}

{{setvar::StyleGuidelines::♢ * [STYLE] Style Guidelines
Use iceberg prose: short sentences, concrete action, visible pressure, and emotion held below the waterline. Name objects, weather, work, drink, food, weapons, rooms, and movement exactly. Let implication carry the pain.}}

{{setvar::DistinctVoice::♢ * [STYLE] Distinct Voice
Give speakers clean surface speech with buried stakes. People say what can be said and leave the rest for timing, repetition, and silence. Class, profession, nationality, and courage should shape word choice without decoration.}}

{{setvar::ImperfectSpeech::♢ * [STYLE] Imperfect Speech
Use clipped answers, repeated practical questions, and silence after the important line. Characters deflect confession by returning to work, weather, drink, money, or travel. The evasion is the feeling.}}

{{setvar::BodyInSpeech::♢ * [STYLE] Body in Speech
Make action do the emotional work: pouring, fishing, packing, cleaning a weapon, lighting a cigarette, touching a glass, watching a door. A simple movement should change the temperature of the dialogue.}}

{{// @category Writing-Style }}
{{// @tooltip Emotional devastation, slice-of-life to tragedy, visual novel style. }}
{{// @color #3498DB }}
{{// @icon ✍️ }}
{{// @badge STYLE }}
{{// @mutual-exclusive-group Writing-Style }}

{{setvar::StyleGuidelines::♢ * [STYLE] Style Guidelines
Use nakige structure: comedy and daily routine building attachment before loss, miracle, memory, or confession changes the frame. Keep early scenes lively and specific so later tenderness has weight. Emotional payoffs should come from repeated objects, habits, promises, and callbacks.}}

{{setvar::DistinctVoice::♢ * [STYLE] Distinct Voice
Give speakers playful rhythm, teasing, defensive cheer, hidden loneliness, and sudden plain sincerity. Comic bits should become relationship language. A character's recurring joke or odd habit can turn into the scene's emotional key.}}

{{setvar::ImperfectSpeech::♢ * [STYLE] Imperfect Speech
Let speech break when the mask drops. Jokes fail, teasing goes quiet, a repeated phrase lands differently, or a cheerful character cannot finish the ordinary line. Keep the rupture simple and earned.}}

{{setvar::BodyInSpeech::♢ * [STYLE] Body in Speech
Use school rooms, benches, vending machines, umbrellas, food, music, hospital rooms, and seasonal light. Physical beats should turn routine into memory. A familiar gesture returning at the wrong time can carry the scene.}}

{{// @category Writing-Style }}
{{// @tooltip Wordplay, meta-narrative, dialogue-driven, unreliable narrators. }}
{{// @color #3498DB }}
{{// @icon ✍️ }}
{{// @badge STYLE }}
{{// @mutual-exclusive-group Writing-Style }}

{{setvar::StyleGuidelines::♢ * [STYLE] Style Guidelines
Use language as combat: wordplay, taxonomy, contradiction, puzzle logic, and self-aware narration moving at high speed. Let talk create action in real time. Keep the prose clever, dangerous, and structurally playful.}}

{{setvar::DistinctVoice::♢ * [STYLE] Distinct Voice
Give every speaker a verbal weapon: pedantry, teasing, formal precision, childish cruelty, philosophical trap, or theatrical confession. People define terms, split hairs, bait each other, and turn grammar into leverage.}}

{{setvar::ImperfectSpeech::♢ * [STYLE] Imperfect Speech
Use correction, pun recovery, nested aside, and deliberate contradiction. A speaker may restart because a better wording changes the battle. Broken speech should show thought gaming the sentence in real time.}}

{{setvar::BodyInSpeech::♢ * [STYLE] Body in Speech
Make posture part of rhetoric. Tilting a head, stepping too close, lounging, pointing, hiding hands, or changing eye level should feel like a move in a verbal duel. Physical action punctuates logic.}}

{{// @category Writing-Style }}
{{// @mutual-exclusive-group Writing-Style }}
{{// @tooltip Jane Austen's romantic period style. Social maneuvering, witty banter, elegant satire. }}
{{// @color #E67E22 }}
{{// @icon ✍️ }}
